  "prompt": "Which one is better: the American Dream or the American dream? Dream with a capital letter or not?",
  "response": "Both \"American Dream\" and \"American dream\" are used, but the preferred usage can depend on the context and style guide being followed.\n\n1. **American Dream (Capitalized)**: This is often used when referring to the concept as a proper noun or an ideal. It suggests a specific, well-defined notion that is widely recognized. For example, in academic writing or when discussing the historical and cultural concept, you might see it capitalized.\n\n   Example: \"The American Dream is often associated with the opportunity for prosperity and success.\"\n\n2. **American dream (Lowercase)**: This is used more generally and might be favored in less formal contexts or by style guides that prefer lowercase for such terms unless they are part of a proper noun. It can also be used to suggest a more personal or varied interpretation of the concept.\n\n   Example: \"Many immigrants come to the U.S. in pursuit of their own version of the American dream.\"\n\n**Style Guide Preferences**:\n\n- **AP Style**: Generally prefers lowercase: \"american dream.\"\n- **Chicago Manual of Style**: Might allow for either, depending on context, but often leans toward capitalization when referring to the concept as an ideal: \"American Dream.\"\n\nIn conclusion, both forms are correct, but \"American Dream\" might be more suitable when referring to the concept in a formal or specific sense, while \"American dream\" could be used in more general or personal contexts. Always consider the style guide you are following or the specific context in which you are writing.",
